question:
Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 0 & -1 \\ 
3 & 1 & 0 \\ 
-2 & 1 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find matrix $B$ such that matrices $A$ and $B$ are inverses.

Find $x$ and $y$ such that $\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-2 & 1 \\ 
3 & -4 \end{array}
\right)\left( \begin{array}{rr}
x & 2 \\ 
1 & y \end{array}
\right)=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-3 & 1 \\ 
2 & -14 \end{array}
\right)$.

Find $a$ such that the matrix $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
1 & 2 & 3 \\ 
4 & 5 & 6 \\ 
3 & 2 & a \end{array}
\right)$ is singular.
